We actually played with something something similar (in https://github.com/pq/logs) and you're right, for http strictly, no framework changes are needed.  Maybe you can use that as a jumping off point?

If you're curious, here's an example of how you'd use it.

1. start w/ some source that makes an http call (I used https://flutter.io/docs/cookbook/networking/fetch-data#complete-example)

2. add a new package dependency on `logs`:

```
  logs:
    git: https://github.com/pq/logs.git
```

3. call the enable logging function in main:

```dart
  enableLogging('http');
```

4. run in debug mode

Doing that you should see some basic http logging in the console:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/67586/51074125-15b5fb80-1630-11e9-9181-9729b95b1428.png)

Here's the full source of the associated `main.dart` if you want to repro exactly:

```dart
import 'dart:async';
import 'dart:convert';

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;
import 'package:logs/logs.dart';

Future<Post> fetchPost() async {
  final response =
  await http.get('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1');

  if (response.statusCode == 200) {
    // If the call to the server was successful, parse the JSON
    return Post.fromJson(json.decode(response.body));
  } else {
    // If that call was not successful, throw an error.
    throw Exception('Failed to load post');
  }
}

class Post {
  final int userId;
  final int id;
  final String title;
  final String body;

  Post({this.userId, this.id, this.title, this.body});

  factory Post.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) {
    return Post(
      userId: json['userId'],
      id: json['id'],
      title: json['title'],
      body: json['body'],
    );
  }
}

void main() {
  enableLogging('http');
  runApp(MyApp(post: fetchPost()));
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  final Future<Post> post;

  MyApp({Key key, this.post}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Fetch Data Example',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: Text('Fetch Data Example'),
        ),
        body: Center(
          child: FutureBuilder<Post>(
            future: post,
            builder: (context, snapshot) {
              if (snapshot.hasData) {
                return Text(snapshot.data.title);
              } else if (snapshot.hasError) {
                return Text("${snapshot.error}");
              }

              // By default, show a loading spinner
              return CircularProgressIndicator();
            },
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

